



SOLUTION:

Method 1: Individual Server Configuration
For stapp01:
bash
ssh tony@stapp01

# Create the group
sudo groupadd nautilus_admin_users

# Check if user rajesh exists, if not create it
id rajesh || sudo useradd rajesh

# Add rajesh to the group
sudo usermod -aG nautilus_admin_users rajesh

# Verify
id rajesh
groups rajesh
For stapp02:
bash
ssh steve@stapp02

# Create the group
sudo groupadd nautilus_admin_users

# Check if user rajesh exists, if not create it
id rajesh || sudo useradd rajesh

# Add rajesh to the group
sudo usermod -aG nautilus_admin_users rajesh

# Verify
id rajesh
groups rajesh
For stapp03:
bash
ssh banner@stapp03

# Create the group
sudo groupadd nautilus_admin_users

# Check if user rajesh exists, if not create it
id rajesh || sudo useradd rajesh

# Add rajesh to the group
sudo usermod -aG nautilus_admin_users rajesh

# Verify
id rajesh
groups rajesh
Method 2: Using a Script (More Efficient)
Create a script to run on all servers:

bash
#!/bin/bash

# Create group
sudo groupadd nautilus_admin_users

# Create user if doesn't exist and add to group
if id "rajesh" &>/dev/null; then
    echo "User rajesh exists, adding to group"
    sudo usermod -aG nautilus_admin_users rajesh
else
    echo "Creating user rajesh and adding to group"
    sudo useradd -G nautilus_admin_users rajesh
fi

# Verification
echo "Verification:"
id rajesh
groups rajesh
Method 3: One-liner for each server
stapp01:
bash
ssh tony@stapp01 'sudo groupadd nautilus_admin_users; id rajesh || sudo useradd rajesh; sudo usermod -aG nautilus_admin_users rajesh; id rajesh'
stapp02:
bash
ssh steve@stapp02 'sudo groupadd nautilus_admin_users; id rajesh || sudo useradd rajesh; sudo usermod -aG nautilus_admin_users rajesh; id rajesh'
stapp03:
bash
ssh banner@stapp03 'sudo groupadd nautilus_admin_users; id rajesh || sudo useradd rajesh; sudo usermod -aG nautilus_admin_users rajesh; id rajesh'
Verification Commands:
After executing on each server, verify with these commands:

bash
# Check if group exists
getent group nautilus_admin_users

# Check user details and group membership
id rajesh
groups rajesh

# Verify user is in the group
getent group nautilus_admin_users | grep rajesh
Expected Output:
The verification should show:

Group nautilus_admin_users exists with GID

User rajesh exists and is member of nautilus_admin_users group

The groups line for rajesh should include nautilus_admin_users

Complete Solution Sequence:
Start with stapp01:

bash
ssh tony@stapp01
sudo groupadd nautilus_admin_users
id rajesh || sudo useradd rajesh
sudo usermod -aG nautilus_admin_users rajesh
id rajesh
Move to stapp02:

bash
ssh steve@stapp02  
sudo groupadd nautilus_admin_users
id rajesh || sudo useradd rajesh
sudo usermod -aG nautilus_admin_users rajesh
id rajesh
Finish with stapp03:

bash
ssh banner@stapp03
sudo groupadd nautilus_admin_users
id rajesh || sudo useradd rajesh
sudo usermod -aG nautilus_admin_users rajesh
id rajesh
This approach ensures that the nautilus_admin_users group is 
created and user rajesh is added to it across all three 
App servers in the Stratos Datacenter.